\par 5.}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054 My }{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062 Reply To Naubol
\par 
\par Just as an opening, this is going to
 be my conceptual testing grounds for systems, testing whether, in the end, I can improve them, change them, or not. Coding comes later. Therefore, I'll reply with the purpose of proving to myself first and foremost, that the system is sound, or if necess
ary, changing completely my stance on an idea, as the situation calls for. Therefore, take nothing in them personally.
\par 
\par 
\par True, Roleplaying is an ooc manifestation of the player and all characters would hypothetically roleplay themselves equally well, that i
s to say, perfectly, since they would -be- themselves. However, just as in theatre, the player who lies the best is the best. Roleplaying experience [hereafter Rxp] -is- an ooc reward for an ooc thing. The player acts well according to the estimation of o
ther players, so oocly he/she gets points to change that tool, the character, further. The character is not getting advantages from being himself, it is instead just fate/destiny/the story that he gets the new attributes.
\par 
\par [*Begin Side note* Skills/spells, once learned, can only be practiced by use, not by pathetic }{\f1\fs20\insrsid4018556 facsimiles}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062  of use}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054  *cough* typing prac <skill> *cough*}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062 
. The practice system is far too open to spamming abuse}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054  and getting every skill to \'93max\'94}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062 
. Of course, the frequency of use that determines whether certain skills get better would be another of those groups of things that need to be easily alterable. Perhaps if there was a group modifier for}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054 
 the skills it would make sense, i.e. not using your bladed weapons skills would weaken all skills in that group, not just \'93longsword use\'94}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062 
\par I envision a}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054 n exponential}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062  system as follows: being taught a skill gives the character a value of 1 in that skill, which thereafter must be raised by use. To ge
t the skill from 9% to 10% might take a total of 10x uses and 99% to 100% would take 100x uses. The x value [decimals or integers apply just as well] could be altered according to skill grouping, e.g. bladed weapons, riding, etc. Therefore, perfection wou
ld be essential}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054 ly }{\f1\fs20\insrsid4018556 unattainable}{\f1\fs20\insrsid5078054 , as it should be, since it doesn\rquote t really exist.}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062 
\par For example, if skills from the bladed weapons group are being mastered too quickly by characters who therefore gain the benefit of that higher skill unduly, the x variable could be changed to a higher value, 
meaning more uses would be necessary. *End Side Note*]
\par 
\par As for roleplaying experience, let's say that player dnaexmosn gets some Rxp and uses them to have char Naex learn a non-combat spell from a teacher. Naex would then have learned that ability icly. Tr
ue, it would have been dependent upon the existence of that those ooc Rxp, but this is the quandary of mudding, it's impossible to have everything ic, you're typing at a text terminal and you don't feel like dying if your character does, how much more ooc
 can you get? Only a fraction of mudding is ic, and it will always depend upon ooc, but the more ic, the better.
\par 
\par 
\par It was a preliminary stipulation that this was a roleplaying mud, therefore enjoyment of roleplaying is the goal. With that in mind, rewards f
or roleplaying well, judged by the players and limited by the imms, would seem to be the perfect option. Not only that, but it is far too often that roleplaying is "encouraged" or "enforced" yet there really is only negative feedback for bad roleplaying, 
n
o positive feedback for good roleplaying. Certainly one must always be sure that the players understand the distinction between "good roleplaying" and "he helped my character", a division that must be laid out firmly and clearly. To aid this, new -players
-, not characters but players, would be unable to refer other players for Rxp, on the premise that they are not necessarily valid judges. After a time, they would lose their newbie status [linked with many other things as well] and would join the process.

\par 
\par 
\par One: The paired builders would still be under the general direction of more experienced imms, but they would have immediate resources in the [one or more] other person who knows their area while they were building it and prior to final review, able to off
er who could offer advice and aid. This would also free up the time of the more experienced imm more.
\par Two: Trust should not be an issue, nor is it, as there are the }{\f1\fs20\insrsid4018556 fail safes}{\f1\fs20\insrsid11354062  of the final reviewer and the other builder to catch problems, accidental or othe
rwise, of each builder. Not just one, but at least two for every area. If a beginning builder disappears after the first day, then someone else on the team takes that builders place to review/help in lieu of the one lost and has access to olc of the area.

\par Three: Speed of builders, not a problem, as when one builder finished, they would presumably go on to another task, which if it was building, could continue to be watched by the slower builder. If it was not building, then the slow builder's watcher posit
ion is simply finished, unless there is another area being started by a different builder. It's not necessary for two builders to always be paired together, the system is more fluid than that.
\par 
\par 
\par All that I can say is that they both have their uses, and that really, it's hard to judge which has more flexibility for a certain task, much less overall. Of course, I'm trying to keep coding completely out of these ideas until I know exactly what I want
, then I can set to the next step of seeing if it's possible.
\par 
